/*
https://leetcode.com/problems/construct-binary-tree-from-inorder-and-postorder-traversal/description/

Given two integer arrays inorder and postorder where inorder is the inorder traversal of a binary tree and postorder is the postorder traversal of the same tree, construct and return the binary tree.

 

Example 1:


Input: inorder = [9,3,15,20,7], postorder = [9,15,7,20,3]
Output: [3,9,20,null,null,15,7]
Example 2:

Input: inorder = [-1], postorder = [-1]
Output: [-1]
 

Constraints:

1 <= inorder.length <= 3000
postorder.length == inorder.length
-3000 <= inorder[i], postorder[i] <= 3000
inorder and postorder consist of unique values.
Each value of postorder also appears in inorder.
inorder is guaranteed to be the inorder traversal of the tree.
postorder is guaranteed to be the postorder traversal of the tree.



*/

/*
To rebuild a binary tree from **inorder** and **postorder** traversals:

* **Inorder**: `left, root, right`
* **Postorder**: `left, right, root` (so the **last** element is the current subtree’s root)

### Key idea

1. The last element in `postorder` is the **root**.
2. Find that root in `inorder` → it splits the inorder array into **left** and **right** subtrees.
3. Recurse on the right subtree **first**, then left, because we consume `postorder` **from the end** (order becomes `root, right, left` when moving backwards).

This runs in **O(n)** using a hashmap from node value → inorder index.

---
*/
### Java (recursive, O(n) time, O(n) space)

```java
import java.util.*;

// Definition for a binary tree node.
class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left, right;
    TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
}

class Solution {
    private int postIdx;
    private Map<Integer, Integer> inIndex; // value -> index in inorder

    public TreeNode buildTree(int[] inorder, int[] postorder) {
        if (inorder == null || postorder == null || inorder.length != postorder.length)
            return null;

        int n = inorder.length;
        inIndex = new HashMap<>(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            inIndex.put(inorder[i], i);
        }

        postIdx = n - 1; // start from the end of postorder
        return build(inorder, postorder, 0, n - 1);
    }

    // Build subtree whose inorder range is [inL .. inR]
    private TreeNode build(int[] inorder, int[] postorder, int inL, int inR) {
        if (inL > inR) return null;

        // Current root is the last unused element in postorder
        int rootVal = postorder[postIdx--];
        TreeNode root = new TreeNode(rootVal);

        // Split inorder at root position
        int mid = inIndex.get(rootVal);

        // IMPORTANT: build right subtree first (because postorder is consumed from the end: root <- right <- left)
        root.right = build(inorder, postorder, mid + 1, inR);
        root.left  = build(inorder, postorder, inL, mid - 1);

        return root;
    }
}
/*

#### Why right first?

Postorder when read **backwards** is: `root, right, left`. After taking `root`, the next elements belong to the **right** subtree, so we must recurse right before left.

---

### Tiny dry run

```
inorder   = [9, 3, 15, 20, 7]
postorder = [9, 15, 7, 20, 3]
```

* postIdx at last → root = 3. In inorder, 3 splits to left `[9]`, right `[15,20,7]`.
* Next post element is 20’s subtree (right first), etc.
* Final tree:
  3
  /&#x20;
  9  20
  / &#x20;
  15   7

---

### Notes / Pitfalls

* Assumes **all node values are unique** (standard for this problem); duplicates would break the map lookup.
* Indices-based recursion avoids extra array copies.
* **Time:** O(n) (each node/edge processed once)
  **Space:** O(n) for map + recursion stack (worst-case skewed tree)

If you want an **iterative stack** version as well, say the word and I’ll add it.

